ce:section.ce:para:
Large-surface-area porous carbon is widely used as the electrode material for supercapacitors owing to its robust electrical double-layer kinetics, moderate conductivity, and outstanding electrochemical stability [1,2]. With the increasing demand for miniaturized and lightweight devices, the volumetric capacitance (Cv
                     ) of porous carbon has become a more reliable parameter than the gravimetric capacitance (Cg
                     ) to evaluate its application performance, especially when the devices should be installed in limited space [3–5]. However, because of the structural contradiction between well-developed pores, sufficient ion transport channels, and high density, it is a big challenge to improve Cv
                      and maintain good rate performance of porous carbon considering the equation Cv = Cg × ρ (ρ is the density of electrode materials) and the fast ion migration kinetics.

The surface area and porous structure of the samples are first measured by the N2 adsorption–desorption isotherms (Fig. 2
                     a). CPC and SPC show a similar type I isotherm with rapid adsorption in the low relative pressure region (P/P0 < 0.1) and very small but detectable hysteresis loops in the middle-pressure region, demonstrating their micropore-dominated structure with a small amount of mesopores (Fig. 2b, Fig. S7 and Table 1
                     ). CPC has an obviously higher adsorption quantity, indicating a higher specific surface area of 2,007 m2 g−1 than SPC of 1,404 m2 g−1. Importantly, CPC integrates both high surface area and compact density compared with other reported porous carbon materials (Fig. 2c), which should be favorable for compact energy storage [21,37–48].
